**AR(1) Process: Stationarity Conditions.** $X_{t} = \phi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon_{t}$, $\varepsilon_{t}\stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim}N(0,\sigma^{2})$. \begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph{*})]\item For what values of $\phi$ is this covariance-stationary?

\item Under stationarity, find $\mathbb{E}[X_{t}]$, $\text{Var}(X_{t})$, and $\rho(k)=\text{Corr}(X_{t},X_{t-k})$.

\item What happens if $|\phi|>1$?\end{enumerate}

**Random Walk vs Stationary AR(1).** $Y_{t} = Y_{t-1}+\varepsilon_{t}$ (random walk) and $X_{t}=0.5X_{t-1}+\varepsilon_{t}$ (AR(1)), both with $\varepsilon_{t}\stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim}N(0,1)$. \begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph{*})]\item Is $Y_{t}$ stationary? Compute its mean and variance as functions of $t$.

\item Is $X_{t}$ stationary? Justify.

\item Sketch the ACF of each. What is the key practical difference for forecasting?\end{enumerate}

blocks.solution:
**(a) Random walk $Y_{t**$.}

Not stationary. Unrolling: $Y_{t} = Y_{0} + \sum_{s=1}^{t}\varepsilon_{s}$. \[\mathbb{E}[Y_{t}] = Y_{0} \quad (\text{constant})\] \[\text{Var}(Y_{t}) = t\cdot\text{Var}(\varepsilon) = t\] The variance grows linearly in $t$ ÔÇö violating the constant variance requirement for stationarity.

**(b) AR(1) $X_{t**$.}

Stationary, since $|\phi|=0.5<1$. $\mathbb{E}[X_{t}]=0$, $\text{Var}(X_{t})=1/(1-0.25)=4/3$ (constant for all $t$).

**(c) ACF comparison.**

 <table class="course-table"><tr><td></td><td>Random walk $Y_{t}$</td><td>AR(1) $X_{t}$ ($\phi=0.5$)</td></tr><tr><td>$\rho(k)$</td><td>$\approx 1$ for all $k$ (slowly decays to 0)</td><td>$0.5^{k}$ (geometric decay)</td></tr><tr><td>Practical shape</td><td>Stays near 1 for large $k$</td><td>Drops quickly (e.g.\ $\rho(5)=0.031$)</td></tr></table>

The random walk's sample ACF stays close to 1 for many lags because $\text{Corr}(Y_{t}, Y_{t-k}) = \sqrt{(t-k)/t}\to 1$ as $t\to\infty$. The AR(1) ACF decays to zero quickly.

**Forecasting implications.** \begin{itemize}\item **AR(1):** Forecast reverts to zero at rate $\phi^{h}$. $\mathbb{E}[X_{t+h}\mid X_{t}]=0.5^{h} X_{t}\to0$.

\item **Random walk:** Best forecast is the current value: $\mathbb{E}[Y_{t+h}\mid Y_{t}]=Y_{t}$ for all $h$ (no mean reversion; forecast error variance $= h$ grows with horizon).\end{itemize}

**Key takeaway:** A random walk has ACF near 1 for all lags; AR(1) with $|\phi|<1$ has geometrically decaying ACF. In finance, asset *prices* resemble random walks (non-stationary) while *returns* are approximately stationary.
